00:09:51,140 --> 00:09:56,460
it takes for the influence of one charge to reach another is always the distance between them divided

147
00:09:56,460 --> 00:10:03,600
by c. By contrast, the speed that's relevant to an index of refraction is how fast the crest of one

148
00:10:03,600 --> 00:10:08,920
of those waves is moving. This is known as the phase velocity. That phase velocity is what

149
00:10:08,920 --> 00:10:14,080
determines how much the wave gets scrunched up, which in turn determines how much it refracts or

150
00:10:14,080 --> 00:10:18,540
bends, which is part of the reason I think it's very good terminology to call this the index of

151
00:10:18,540 --> 00:10:24,860
refraction rather than say the index of slowing. In general, the electric field inside a medium like

152
00:10:24,860 --> 00:10:31,280
glass is this incredibly complicated sum of a whole bunch of propagating influences from every

153
00:10:31,280 --> 00:10:36,040
one of the wiggling charges in that material, all together with the incoming light wave. But

154
00:10:36,040 --> 00:10:41,900
importantly, all of those individual propagations are traveling at c, never slower, never faster.

155
00:10:41,900 --> 00:10:47,300
It is miraculous that the way that these combine can be described simply at all, and that it's not

156
00:10:47,300 --> 00:10:52,620
some monstrously intractable mess. But we are fortunate, and when you add them all up, the net

157
00:10:52,620 --> 00:10:58,720
effect can be described cleanly, and it looks just like a sine wave, one whose phase velocity happens

158
00:10:58,720 --> 00:11:03,260
to be different from c. Another thing to keep in mind if it seems very weird for these wave

159
00:11:03,260 --> 00:11:09,260
crests to move faster than c is that everything in this explanation depends very heavily on things

160
00:11:09,260 --> 00:11:14,940
being in a steady state. That's very different from say, trying to send information through the medium

161
00:11:14,940 --> 00:11:20,480
with a little pulse of light. This is what Mithana explores in her videos on the index of refraction

